<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR]]></title><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/most-popular/<atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/theatlantic/most-popular" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 16 日，星期日 12:11:55 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Delivery Apps Just Did the Impossible]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>硅谷正在用自己的游戏打败多米诺骨牌。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/AGu-O9jBTio589Oh61_Rq-CVEfE=/0x0:5337x3002/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_492047870/original.jpg" alt="顶部带有多米诺骨牌标志的送货车" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>丹尼尔·阿克/彭博/盖蒂</figcaption></figure>近年来，达美乐<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.forbes.com/sites/aliciakelso/2018/04/30/delivery-digital-provide-dominos-with-game-changing-advantages/">有时</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.forbes.com/sites/aliciakelso/2018/04/30/delivery-digital-provide-dominos-with-game-changing-advantages/">自诩为</a>一家以送<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.forbes.com/sites/aliciakelso/2018/04/30/delivery-digital-provide-dominos-with-game-changing-advantages/">披萨</a>为副业的科技公司。这是真的。通过改进人工智能、GPS、 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/06/17/dominos-will-start-delivering-pizzas-via-an-autonomous-robot-this-fall/">自动驾驶汽车</a>和增强现实等技术，全球最大的披萨连锁店将送餐这一黑暗艺术变成了一门科学。这一切都始于其著名的 Pizza Tracker，该产品于 2008 年推出，并创建了跟踪食品配送的早期标准。 Domino&#39;s 现在有大约<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://digiday.com/marketing/dominos-house-technology-push-helped-increase-online-orders/">15 种不同的</a>披萨订购<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://digiday.com/marketing/dominos-house-technology-push-helped-increase-online-orders/">方式</a>，包括语音助手、Facebook Messenger、Slack 和一个<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://time.com/4283913/dominos-zero-click-ordering-app/">“零点击”应用程序</a>，可在 10 秒后自动为您订购。<br><br>所有这些技术帮助达美乐增加了销售额并简化了运营，使其最终<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnbc.com/2020/11/25/why-pizza-hut-is-struggling-to-against-dominos-and-papa-johns.html">“超越了小屋披萨”</a> ，成为美国<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://ir.dominos.com/news-releases/news-release-details/dominos-pizzar-announces-third-quarter-2022-financial-results">约</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://ir.dominos.com/news-releases/news-release-details/dominos-pizzar-announces-third-quarter-2022-financial-results">三分之一</a>披萨外卖的服务商。其他餐厅，无论是披萨店还是其他餐厅，都已经开始依赖一系列第三方应用程序，而达美乐则将一切都保留在内部，这意味着它处于领先地位 - 从理论上讲，您也是如此。没有邮递员，没问题：只需<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.dominos.com/en/pages/order/#!/checkout/">9.99 美元左右</a>，加上少量费用和小费，多米诺 (Domino) 司机就会送出一份达美乐 (Domino) 披萨，30 分钟内就会送到您家门口。<br><br>但本周早些时候，达美乐<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/dominos-pizza-strikes-deal-with-uber-in-search-for-new-sales-4e6b21fd">宣布</a>它也将与一款送货应用程序合作。到 2023 年底，大多数地方的饥饿群众将能够通过 Uber Eats 订购达美乐 (Domino) 馅饼和各种钠炸弹（尽管达美乐 (Domino) 的司机仍将送餐）。通过与 Uber 联手，该公司承认 DoorDash、Uber Eats 和 Grubhub 等外卖应用程序已成为主导地位——使用它们已接近餐厅维持生计的必要要求。如果 Domino&#39;s 都无法摆脱送货应用程序，那么还有谁可以呢？<br><br>恰如其分的是，美国的送餐热潮实际上是从达美乐开始的。该公司<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/1986/09/27/business/pizza-s-home-delivery-war.html">经常被认为</a>推广了披萨外卖的概念（ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/01/pizza-delivery-box-design-soggy/672712/">它</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/01/pizza-delivery-box-design-soggy/672712/">创造了现代披萨盒</a>，联合创始人汤姆·莫纳汉甚至在送披萨时<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2007/02/19/the-deliverer">遇见了他的妻子</a>）。尽管披萨订购从固定电话和手机转向通过移动应用程序拨号，但以送货为中心的多米诺骨牌模式却拥有惊人的寿命。 2011 年，时任首席执行官帕特里克·多伊尔 (Patrick Doyle) 开始了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://pizzaturnaround.com/">一场不太可能的全国性广告活动</a>，承认他的披萨有点糟糕，不久后，他向他的技术团队<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncr.com/blogs/restaurants/digital-innovations-dominos">发出了挑战</a>：他希望订购披萨变得足够简单，以便有人可以在等待时完成在红绿灯处。移动点餐是未来，未来，披萨点餐只需 17 秒。<br><br>从某种意义上说，达美乐已经成为其自身成功的受害者。该公司的技术悟性帮助公众做好了不仅仅是披萨外卖的准备。这些第三方应用程序出现在 2010 年代零工经济繁荣时期，然后在疫情早期爆发。随着疫情放缓，食品配送销售本可以重蹈 Peloton 的覆辙，但<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www2.deloitte.com/us/en/pages/consumer-business/articles/future-of-restaurants-study.html">事实并非如此</a>。去年，大约 14% 的披萨销量是通过外卖应用程序<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/dominos-pizza-strikes-deal-with-uber-in-search-for-new-sales-4e6b21fd">完成的</a>，此外还有一系列让餐厅菜单看起来平淡无奇的菜肴和菜肴。截至 2023 年，数十万家餐厅都使用了外卖应用，提供高级餐厅的干式熟成牛排和麦当劳的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.mcdonalds.com/us/en-us/product/steak-egg-cheese-bagel.html">干式牛排百吉饼</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.mcdonalds.com/us/en-us/product/steak-egg-cheese-bagel.html">。</a>餐厅的餐厅可能会再次爆满，但这些应用程序<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://secondmeasure.com/datapoints/food-delivery-services-grubhub-uber-eats-doordash-postmates/">现在带来的收入比以往任何时候都多</a>。<br><br>换句话说，它们已经变得太大而不容忽视。尽管达美乐将继续提供自己的披萨，但其首席执行官拉塞尔·韦纳 (Russell Weiner) 在讨论 Uber Eats 优食交易时，用简单的语言<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.restaurantbusinessonline.com/financing/dominos-uber-eats-deal-acknowledges-reality-third-party-marketplace">表达了错过的成本</a>：“聚合平台上发生了 50 亿美元的披萨销售额……[那]我们应该有三分之一。”<br><br>随着数以百万计的餐厅员工准备订单和数以百万计的零工为他们送货，整个食品配送生态系统已经合并，这对餐厅和整个餐饮文化都产生了巨大的影响。这些应用程序可以向餐厅收取<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/politics-and-government/clark-county/clark-county-caps-third-party-food-delivery-fees-at-15-2087939/">高达</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/politics-and-government/clark-county/clark-county-caps-third-party-food-delivery-fees-at-15-2087939/">30% 的</a>费用，这给利润本来就很紧张的企业带来了沉重的负担，需要大量的订单量才能实现收支平衡。他们拥有如此大的权力，以至于他们现在正在影响<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://get.grubhub.com/blog/delivery-menu-tips/">餐馆的菜单</a>，有时即使你在里面用餐。与此同时，承担所有这些职能的送货员仍然作为独立承包商获得低工资，没有任何保护或讨价还价的能力。<br><br>对于食客来说，将科技进一步引入餐饮业是有成本的。根据 2021 年的一份报告，送餐应用程序与社交媒体巨头<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.pcmag.com/how-to/social-media-and-food-delivery-apps-sell-the-most-personal-data">并驾齐驱</a>，成为消费者个人数据的最大收集者和兜售者。多米诺<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/dominos-pizza-strikes-deal-with-uber-in-search-for-new-sales-4e6b21fd">自己承认</a>，Uber 愿意交出客户数据是其决定与该公司达成协议的关键因素。即使在沙发上订购任何东西变得更加容易和方便，外卖应用程序将继续迫使餐厅调整其运营以适应他们的需求。无论您每天晚上都订购送货服务还是根本没有使用过应用程序，这一点都很重要。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 15 Jul 2023 12:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/dominos-deliver-uber-eats-app/674716/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/dominos-deliver-uber-eats-app/674716/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Sympathy for the Theater Kids]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div><em>戏剧营</em>是对创造力的一首可爱的颂歌，并提醒人们艺术社区的重要性。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/oewehFWQkvJiMJ3QeRziMcrPUPs=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/theater_camp_hr/original.jpg" alt="电影《剧场营》中的人物" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>探照灯图片</figcaption></figure>忘记<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://time.com/6293844/barbie-oppenheimer-internet-phenomenon/"><em>巴本海默</em></a>吧；七月有一个不同的双重特征你应该注意。本周末首映的两部电影颂扬了实际制作的价值。其中之一是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/mission-impossible-dead-reckoning-review/674610/">最新的<em>《碟中谍》</em></a> ，这是一次令人心旷神怡、惊险刺激的旅程。另一部是<em>《戏剧营》</em> ，一部伪纪录片，向汤姆·克鲁斯致歉，可能会更好地强调他的信息，即将一生奉献给艺术的重要性（并且在大约一半的时间里也是如此）。<br><br>这部深受观众喜爱的圣丹斯电影讲述了阿迪朗达克山脉一个小型但受人喜爱的暑期机构的一群乌合之众的辅导员的故事，该机构恰如其分地称为“AdirondACTS”。大部分情节——部分是通过上演《大秀》来拯救阿迪朗德表演艺术中心免于丧失抵押品赎回权的故事——对于任何看过众多有关表演艺术节目的电影之一的人来说，都会感到熟悉（ <em>《坎普》</em> 、 <em>《摇滚夏令营</em>》，以及其他与<em>《坎普》</em>相关的电影）在标题中）。尽管这部电影的叙述很简单，但<em>《戏剧营》</em>却非常迷人，而且与时俱进，它出现在作家和演员因担心自己的作品贬值而<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/live/2023/07/13/business/actors-strike-sag#sag-aftra-writers-strike">罢工</a>的时代。因此，这部电影对创造力进行了可爱的审视，同时也令人惊讶地深刻地提醒我们，大多数艺术家的成功不是通过个人天才，而是通过成为社区的一部分。<br><br><em>剧院训练营</em>以 AdirondACTS 的创始人琼（艾米·塞达里斯饰演）开始，她受伤了：在中学制作《<em>再见小鸟》</em>时使用的闪光灯导致癫痫发作，使她陷入昏迷。一群古怪的人挺身而出拯救营地，其中包括琼的懒儿子特洛伊（吉米·塔特罗，搞笑饰）；自以为严肃的戏剧教练阿莫斯（本·普拉特，为可怕的<em>《亲爱的埃文·汉森》</em>电影做了巨大的弥补）；古怪的音乐老师丽贝卡·黛安（莫莉·戈登，本片的联合导演和编剧）；夸夸其谈的舞蹈教练克莱夫（内森·李·格雷厄姆饰）；令人愉快的是，工作人员的新成员珍妮特（阿约·艾德比里饰）在简历中谎报了她的舞台工作诚意。孩子们也很出色：<em>米纳</em>里的艾伦·金（Alan Kim）在几个场景中脱颖而出，饰演一名一心想成为人才经纪人的营员，他像一个小小的阿里·戈尔德（Ari Gold）一样对着营地行政办公室的电话大声叫喊。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/mission-impossible-dead-reckoning-review/674610/">阅读：好莱坞最佳动作片的真诚与荒谬</a><br><br>如果这些演员只是在整部电影中互相模仿，那么<em>戏剧营</em>就足够有趣了。但剧本明智地花时间探索为什么任何成年人都想在夏天里追逐那些想成为托尼奖得主的小人物——反过来，这些露营者从周围不拘一格的成年人中得到了什么。戈登和联合导演尼克·利伯曼使用极端特写镜头，并将相机偷窥地放在百叶窗后面，强调了工作人员所承受的压力。通过安静的对话和精心挑选的反应镜头，影片揭示了辅导员的不安全感和动机。有些人，比如阿莫斯，曾因职业生涯中的小问题而受到重创，并将阿迪朗德行动视为避风港。其他人，比如克莱夫，沉浸在怀旧之中，向有鉴赏力的观众分享他们过去的艺术故事。<br><br>对话可能会变得有点俗气——“我们是剧院人；我们知道如何把纸板变成金子。”一个角色在某一时刻坚持说，但这部电影用一些场景来平衡这一点，这些场景取笑了戏剧人、孩子或成人的荒谬。辅导员常常对他们的受监护人非常诚实，提醒他们很少有人能够进入百老汇。在员工会议期间，他们以一种严肃的态度批评孩子们的表现。在我最喜欢的场景之一中，丽贝卡-黛安和阿莫斯突然袭击了一名露营者，这名露营者使用了催泪棒——演员们使用催泪棒的工具，可以帮助他们在提示时哭泣——他们跳上舞台，以缉毒局特工的力度没收了催泪棒。破坏毒品交易。露营者立即对自己的行为感到抱歉，但丽贝卡-黛安用泪棒在<em>自己身上</em>，只是为了强调她对学生有多么失望。这是强调孩子们和工作人员之间联系的几个幽默笑话之一。<br><br><em>剧院营地</em>既真诚又荒唐，明确表示像 AdirondACTS 这样的地方是神奇怪异的缩影。这部电影不仅仅是对戏剧奇迹的幻想颂歌，更是对戏剧奇迹的颂歌。它探讨了追随一个人的激情如何需要巨大的支持。绩效在于表达，对于大多数员工来说，承认他们在一个特别艰难的夏天（士气低落、收入低）的感受会促使他们学习与营员相同的课程。特洛伊必须弄清楚自己作为营地临时所有者的角色，而不是拖延和与试图说服他出售财产的有吸引力的财务顾问（帕蒂·哈里森，总是受欢迎的存在）鬼混。阿莫斯必须学会依赖丽贝卡-黛安而不让她窒息，就像她是他在戏剧中的场景搭档一样。他们只有齐心协力才能拯救代表他们​​的营地。这种使命并不能拯救世界——但话又说回来，舞台再小，<em>也是</em>他们的整个世界。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 15 Jul 2023 12:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/theater-camp-movie-review/674712/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/theater-camp-movie-review/674712/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Why YIMBY Righteousness Backfires]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>将郊区居民视为可恨的势利小人并不会让他们更欢迎新来者。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/owUJAAHGITBEG0A2viEAgvjioqE=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/YIMBY/original.jpg" alt="加利福尼亚州安提阿的郊区房屋" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>杰森·亨利 / 纽约时报 / Redux</figcaption></figure>如果想要生活在一个主要居民能够轻松负担过高房价的田园社区是错误的，那么大多数美国人也不想是对的。<br><br>这是YIMBY（“Yes in My Backyard”）运动面临的核心挑战，该运动是一个由学者、政策制定者和草根活动家组成的意识形态多元化的组织，致力于一个简单到令人解除武装的想法，即在美国最繁荣的城镇建造新家园将是一件非常好的事情。作为一个智力项目，YIMBYism 取得了巨大的成功，这是有充分理由的。大量证据表明，增加住房供应以满足住房需求可以 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/mac.20170388">促进经济增长</a>并<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.urban.org/sites/default/files/publication/103472/why-housing-matters-for-upward-mobility-evidence-and-indicators-for-practitioners-and-policymakers.pdf">刺激向上流动</a>。甚至有初步证据表明，遏制当地土地使用监管可能有助于<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://corinnelow.github.io/LafortuneLow.pdf">扭转工薪阶层家庭婚姻的崩溃</a>，这可不是一件小事。在研究地方土地利用的经济学家和法律学者中，关于分区改革的争论<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3917621">基本上已经结束</a>。<br><br>然而，YIMBY 运动未能克服选民根深蒂固的怀疑，他们凭直觉认为新家园意味着新邻居，而新邻居可能意味着新的麻烦。<br><br>以加利福尼亚州为例，YIMBY 立法者在那里取得了最大的进步。自 2016 年以来，加利福尼亚州立法机构通过了一系列措施，以取代当地一些最恶劣的土地使用法规，促使<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/10/california-accessory-dwelling-units-legalization-yimby/671648/">附属住宅单元</a>蓬勃发展。但是，尽管有无可争议的证据表明住房负担能力危机仍在迫使数十万低收入和中等收入家庭离开该州，但许多加州人强烈反对最近的住房推动，以至于出现了真正的危险是选民将在 2024 年通过一项<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://ourneighborhoodvoices.com/">投票措施</a>来推翻改革。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/04/california-single-family-zoning-housing/673758/">耶路撒冷德姆萨斯：加州并不特别</a><br><br>为了理解为什么加州选民如此难以赢得支持，陈·扎克伯格倡议（Chan Zuckerberg Initiative）是 YIMBYism 的主要慈善倡导者之一，委托开展了一系列焦点小组和调查，最终于去年发布了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://chanzuckerberg.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/CZI-The-California-Dream-Housing-White-Paper.pdf?_hsmi=202158258&amp;_hsenc=p2ANqtz-8dQATs5ekYbaqhSew-av8OArDJ7C4yOHPrIUsuYhkhO1dam2ool1Zxkycq6j036i1tXC4bn1DOSIMaxaVITCf_Crl2SrOS70pC7rP7s8X1jQ_TpxA">一份报告</a>。作者表示，“我们听到的大多数租客和业主都表示，他们对附近的经济适用房解决方案持谨慎态度，担心这会导致犯罪、噪音、垃圾、非法倾倒以及普遍缺乏财产维护。 ”此外，尽管绝大多数受访者“广泛接受多样性作为其社区当前或理想的特征”，但他们对邻居比他们贫穷得多的想法深感不安。<br><br>这种怀疑并不是金州独有的。今年 1 月，州长凯西·霍赫尔 (Kathy Hochul) 公布了“纽约住房契约”，这是一套雄心勃勃的改革措施，旨在提高纽约市及其臭名昭著的昂贵郊区的住房生产。到五月， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://manhattan.institute/article/nyc-housing-crisis-next-steps-after-new-york-housing-compact-fails">住房契约已经失效</a>。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/07/local-government-power-nimby-denver/674164/">科罗拉多州</a>、亚利桑那州和德克萨斯州的全州分区改革提案也以失败告终。<br><br>这一切并不意味着 YIMBY 主义注定要失败。但如果 YIMBY 想要推动更多美国人朝他们的方向发展，他们最好少些威吓，多些倾听。<br><br>一些最热心的 YIMBY 坚信自己的正义，采取了道德姿态，谴责顽固的房主是势利者或偏执狂，并呼吁采取全面的立法措施，剥夺地方政府的土地使用权，并进一步限制房东的能力。选择他们的租户。理查德·卡伦伯格的新书《 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.amazon.com/Excluded-Zoning-NIMBYism-Class-Build/dp/1541701461"><em>排除》</em></a>是这种情感的完美升华。<br><br>卡伦伯格以其对精英大学种族偏好的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/10/supreme-court-harvard-affirmative-action-legacy-admissions-equity/671869/">逆向批评</a>而闻名，他将自己的公共生活奉献给了种族和经济融合的论证。排除者并不满足于对可能会吸引房主自身利益的排他性分区提出审慎的理由，<em>他们</em>认为这种做法是一种道德上的愤怒——阶级主义，也隐含着种族主义——我们需要一场道德运动来根除它。联邦政府全力出动，仿照上个世纪反对种族隔离的斗争。为此，卡伦伯格呼吁制定一项经济公平住房法案，允许对歧视穷人或对不同阶层产生不必要的不​​同影响的分区政策提出诉讼，并由法官决定什么是必要的。这实际上相当于联邦政府对单户住宅分区的禁令，也会威胁到无数其他分区政策，并且在很大程度上通过基于模糊、主观的法律标准威胁提起昂贵的诉讼来威慑地方政府。<br><br>虽然这一论点肯定会引起一些社会正义进步人士的共鸣，但不太可能说服那些担心社区变化前景的焦虑的房主和租客。加州大学戴维斯分校土地使用法教授克里斯·埃尔门多夫警告说，将分区改革视为经济正义问题可能会适得其反。今天的富裕郊区居民可能会对<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.slowboring.com/p/race-and-zoning">他们犯有种族敌意的说法感到不满</a>，但他们完全乐意被指控为色盲阶级偏见。<br><br>反对在自家后院修建新住房的人可能不是特别开明，但他们也不是妄想。顾名思义，排他性分区是一种通过部署地方土地使用监管来吸引富裕居民并阻止贫困居民来改善地方税基的策略。美国的地方公共服务主要由地方财产税和其他市政收入（例如销售税、停车费和污水处理费）提供资金。人们不必是一个可恨的势利小人，也能认识到，虽然一些新来者在当地创造的收入会多于他们在服务中获得的收入，但其他人却不会。<br><br>事实上，这些地方财政压力可以说是塑造美国支离破碎的大都市地理的核心力量。正如普林斯顿大学经济学家利亚·布斯坦（Leah Boustan） <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://press.princeton.edu/books/hardcover/9780691150871/competition-in-the-promised-land"><em>在《应许之地的竞争》一书中</em></a>指出的那样，战后时代的“白人逃亡”在很大程度上是由这些财政问题驱动的。随着贫穷的黑人移民前往东北部、中西部和西部的城市中心，大量富裕的白人家庭搬到平均收入高于他们离开的城市的郊区管辖区。毫无疑问，这种向外移民的部分原因是白人不愿与黑人邻居一起生活，但由于这一时期美国城市的隔离程度如此之高，大部分逃亡者都来自纯白人社区。城市居民离开这些白人社区的动机不是担心与黑人邻居进行社会交往，而是担心与有不同需求和优先事项的低收入邻居进行财政交往。 “搬到郊区，”布斯坦写道，“让白人家庭能够将自己与中心城市提供的不断变化的当地公共产品和财政义务隔离开来。”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2015/07/white-flight-alive-and-well/399980/">阅读：白色飞行从未结束</a><br><br>鉴于这些强大的财政激励措施，小型郊区司法管辖区的邻避主义几乎是不可避免的。与其指望道德劝说能够改变这些社区的分区政策，YIMBY 人最好采取一种更加谦虚和现实的方法，努力与郊区的邻避者相向而行。<br><br>赢得郊区房主的青睐的一个直接方法是推进住房改革，帮助他们积累财富，正如埃尔门多夫<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.city-journal.org/article/the-housing-treadmill">所建议的</a>那样。例如，附属住宅单元的合法化可以让普通房主富裕起来，无论公平与否，普通房主都比大型开发商享有更多的公众同情，并且可以动员他们反对成本增加的市政影响费和自由裁量审查程序。作为额外的好处，这种改革让 YIMBY 能够在尊重财产权和个人自由的基础上发出<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.city-journal.org/article/where-are-all-the-republican-yimbys">更加乐观的呼吁</a>，这一主张帮助俄勒冈州、犹他州和蒙大拿州通过了分区改革法律。<br><br>当面对坚决的郊区阻力时，例如在纽约州南部，霍赫尔的住房契约被证明是一个巨大的政治负担，YIMBYs 应该集中精力放松大城市的土地使用监管。在人口较多的司法管辖区，对住房建设的反对往往不那么强烈，部分原因是这些地区的贫富居民比例从定义上来说更难改变。城市社区也比郊区社区更具活力：其中租房者、年轻人、低收入家庭和其他住房流失率高于平均水平的人口比例过高。社区变化是这些社区生活的一个事实。如果城市核心区的分区改革取得成功，那么较小社区的住房增长将更加引人注目。<br><br>冒着激怒反商业进步人士的风险，YIMBY 还应该采取更多措施<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.annualreviews.org/doi/full/10.1146/annurev-polisci-051921-102505">培养大型雇主作为政治盟友</a>。较低的住房成本是吸引和留住工人的有力工具，大型雇主可以对州立法机构施加重大影响。加州科技行业的雇主在反对严格分区的斗争中发挥了重要作用并非巧合——他们敏锐地意识到，随着金州住房成本的上涨，他们要么支付更高的工资，要么眼睁睁地看着他们的工人逃往城市在爱达荷州或内华达州。<br><br>最后，YIMBY 应该努力软化最初推动排斥性分区的地方财政激励措施。耶鲁大学法学院的扎卡里·利斯考 (Zachary Liscow) 发现， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nyulawreview.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/NYULawReview-92-6-Liscow.pdf">当各州承担更大比例的学校经费时</a>，富人会变得更愿意搬到较贫穷的司法管辖区，可能是因为这样做将不再让他们承担为大量学生提供支持服务的特殊负担。纳税很少的邻居。与这种模式一致，他发现集中的学校经费导致低收入城市的税收降低。<br><br>类似的逻辑也适用于国家对治安和公共安全工作的资助。如果邻避者担心低收入移民的涌入会导致犯罪和骚乱激增，正如陈·扎克伯格研究所的调查结果强烈表明的那样，那么增加国家对当地执法机构的援助可能会减轻他们的担忧。一些主要的社交媒体左派人士不以为然地将这种支持分区改革和“破窗”监管的结合称为“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://darrellowens.substack.com/p/whos-who-the-dictionary-of-in-my">监狱城市化</a>”，但社交媒体左派当然不是目标受众。<br><br>诚然，改变地方财政激励措施将是一项重大任务，这将遭到选民的抵制，他们担心在新的财政分配下会失败。但地方政府收入的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.urban.org/policy-centers/cross-center-initiatives/state-and-local-finance-initiative/state-and-local-backgrounders/state-and-local-revenues#local">30%</a>已经以州政府转移支付的形式出现。增加州政府为地方警务或公共教育提供资金的责任将是一个相对温和且可能非常受欢迎的变化，特别是与强制生产受契约限制的经济适用住房和其他优先事项的公平份额要求相比。 YIMBY 离开了。<br><br>修改地方财政激励措施、与地区商业精英结成联盟、帮助一些拥有丰富房产的房主变得更富有，不会带来一个从东海岸到西海岸的综合社区的平等新千年，但它将帮助 YIMBY 建立一个更有说服力的案例住房增长符合郊区居民开明的自身利益，否则他们可能会担心税收负担上升和房价下跌。这不是一个糟糕的开始。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 15 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/yimby-california-social-justice-kahlenberg/674714/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/yimby-california-social-justice-kahlenberg/674714/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[A Raunchy Comedy’s Subtle Wisdom]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> <em>Joy Ride</em>知道，回国探亲并不是缓解家里孤独感的简单方法。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/6DFmKkJYZXtH8GYGMiig1wpay1k=/0x92:3000x1780/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/joyride_unit_210927_00234rc2/original.jpg" alt="《欢乐之旅》场景中，中国花园中的四位女性向银幕外望去" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>艾德·阿拉克尔 / 狮门影业</figcaption></figure>诚然，我对<em>Joy Ride表示怀疑。</em>过去几年，典型好莱坞类型的亚裔美国电影越来越多，例如浪漫喜剧、超级英雄大片和慢热剧情片。很多都非常出色，有些则不是那么出色，但在其中几部中，我注意到一个反复出现的主题：主角过于理想化地回到亚洲。一部关于亚裔美国被收养者和她的朋友们去中国<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/joy-ride-bottoms-raunchy-comedies/674691/">的新电影</a><em>《欢乐之旅》</em>似乎准备重演这一比喻。<br><br>但当影片上映 20 分钟时，当我因震惊和笑声而气喘吁吁时，我明白它正在做一些不同的事情。当奥黛丽（阿什利·帕克饰）来到中国时，我更感触到了这一点，并感叹每个人都长得像她。乍一看，你不是一个引人注目的少数群体，这种感觉被赋予了权力，这是关于侨民返乡的电影中相当典型的观察结果。但还没等奥黛丽兴奋起来，她最好的朋友兼旅伴洛洛（雪莉可乐饰）指出，机场里有来自台湾和中国大陆的人，还有光鲜亮丽的韩流明星，他们绕过了海关——而且它们都明显不同。奥黛丽可能会想把这些亚洲面孔视为可以互换的，这样她就能有归属感；洛洛暗示这是一个幻想，而不是现实。<br><br>这也是向观众传达的信息：<em>欢乐之旅</em>有兴趣承认——然后揭开——我所说的祖国比喻。我在过去几年的电影中特别注意到这一点，其中一个亚裔美国人角色前往亚洲，尽管它可以跨文化存在。也许主角是飞往新加坡去见他们富有的男朋友的家人，就像<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2018/08/asian-americas-great-gatsby-moment/568213/"><em>《疯狂的亚洲富人</em></a>》（ <em>Joy Ride</em>的导演兼联合编剧阿黛尔·林 (Adele Lim) 也是这部电影的联合编剧）那样。也许他们正在执行一项奇幻的超级英雄任务，就像漫威的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2021/08/shang-chi-legend-ten-rings-marvel-review/619867/"><em>《上气与十环传奇》</em></a>中那样。或者也许他们在韩国街头街头卖艺，爱上了当地狂躁的精灵梦中女孩，就像安静的独立电影<em>《小说与其他现实》中那样。</em>无论出于何种原因，角色们都通过亚洲之旅来了解自己。有时，祖国比喻可以成为承载主角情感转变的有效结构。但最糟糕的是，它把亚洲国家变成了亚裔美国人主角解决他们在美国的疏远或孤独问题的场所，但却没有将这些国家视为具有自身复杂性或多样性的地方。人们可能会开始觉得这些角色在他们自称是自己的人中间<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.npr.org/2010/08/18/129254808/eat-pray-love-leave-orientalism-still-big-onscreen"><em>“吃、祈祷、爱”</em></a> 。<br><br>以祖国比喻的基石为例：返乡蒙太奇。在<em>《摘金奇缘》</em>中，主角夫妇尼克和瑞秋在新加坡降落后，被带到了一个夜市，友好的邻里阿姨叔叔们一边对他们微笑，一边熟练地准备美味的沙爹和叻沙。在<em>《上气》</em>中，亚裔美国主角在澳门上演了主题相同的场景，飞驰穿过霓虹灯照亮的城市，目瞪口呆地看着街上的舞者和小贩。这两部电影都以第二代美国人经历了深刻的成长为结尾：雷切尔获得了自信（以及丈夫），尚气成为了名副其实的超级英雄。<br><br>乍一看， <em>《欢乐之旅》</em>可能看起来并没有偏离这些大纲情节。故事讲述奥黛丽（Audrey）是一个白人家庭收养的中国人，她与洛洛（Lolo）和她朋友的表弟“神枪手”一起去了中国。最初，她来这里是为了做生意，但由于洛洛的刺激和一些滑稽的情况，她最终利用这次旅行找到了她的亲生母亲。 <em>《欢乐之旅》</em>最终为我们提供了一个半开玩笑版本的熟悉蒙太奇，奥黛丽似乎接受了她的任务：这伙人与当地人一起坐在一辆卡车后面，然后奥黛丽像<em>《音乐之声》</em>那样在一个酒吧前旋转。山景，宣示“我爱中国！”这一幕在洛洛祖母家举行的一场喧闹的聚会中达到高潮，中国大家庭张开双臂欢迎朋友们。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/joy-ride-bottoms-raunchy-comedies/674691/">阅读：请更多带有狂野性爱场面的喜剧</a><br><br>然而， <em>Joy Ride</em>倾向于其过度的感性，并通过眨眼和轻推来提供这些理想化的序列。观众无意将“我心中国”蒙太奇理解为一种简单化的角色发展形式。相反，它是电影更大背景的一部分，推动观众直击内心。首先，奥黛丽对她个人旅程的幸福拥抱是喜剧性的，反映了她的天真。然后，当她最终即将见到她的生母时，她并没有彻底实现自我实现。相反，她得到了关于她的血统的令人惊讶的消息，这改变了她寻找身份的前提。奥黛丽回到美国后并没有顿悟，反而遇到了比离开时更多的麻烦。<br><br>这种复杂的未完成任务的感觉在其他具有类似弧线的电影中也很明显，这些弧线抵制理想化的家园。王璐璐的《 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/07/farewell-lulu-wang-movie-review-awkwafina/593464/"><em>别告诉她》</em></a>遵循了这一叙事，欧亚电影制片人制作的小规模电影也遵循这一叙事，例如周大卫的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/02/return-to-seoul-movie-review/673127/"><em>《重返首尔》</em></a>和洪考乌的<em>《季风》</em> 。这些电影与那些脆弱的同类电影之间的主要区别在于，它们能够使用返校节作为情节设计，但又没有明确暗示它将解决角色的所有问题。在<em>《别告诉她》</em>中，故事的重点不再是主角回到中国能给她带来什么，而是更多地关注她跨越国界的悲伤之旅。在<em>《重返首尔》</em>中，一名被收养者的韩国之行被用来毫不妥协地审视她的矛盾心理和鲁莽行为。<em>季风</em>将主角对家的渴望与他对同性恋的渴望联系起来。所有这些电影都拒绝沉迷于愿望的实现。<br><br> <em>《欢乐之旅》</em>也不例外，它为一部淫秽的喜剧带来了微妙的智慧。奥黛丽的核心需求是归属感和接受度。这部电影并没有让她在国外找到它，而是引导她去寻找那些在操场上支持她或支持她完成大学学业的朋友。朝圣之旅会带你回到一直在那里的亲人身边，这也是女孩或男孩旅行叙事中常见的情节。但考虑到<em>欢乐乘车</em>的文化背景，它巧妙地破坏了祖国的比喻。奥黛丽的朋友们是她的救赎，因为他们是同一个复杂的侨民的一部分，并且知道以特定方式努力归属感是什么感觉。洛洛（Lolo）的性积极艺术作品在她的移民父母经营的餐厅里不受欢迎；另一位朋友凯特（Kat）正拼命地向她高度虔诚的中国未婚夫扮演独身者，尽管她的大学过去很不修边幅。这些女性最终不需要寻找某种神话般的归属感——她们已经属于彼此了。通过让角色认识到这一点， <em>《欢乐之旅》</em>放弃了祖国解决一切问题的义务，并强调了我们称之为家的关系的变革力量。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 15 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/joy-ride-movie-asia-chinese-diaspora/674717/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/joy-ride-movie-asia-chinese-diaspora/674717/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Most Metal Bird Nests You’ll Ever See]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>喜鹊使用防鸟钉来达到自己的目的。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/5fmJSsjXF6lXUEFB0PpeysZzyTw=/0x0:10793x6071/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/Magpie_nest_Antwerp_BE_Photo_Auke_Florian_Hiemstra_copy/original.jpg" alt="用防鸟钉等材料制作的鸟巢照片" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>奥克-弗洛里安·希姆斯特拉</figcaption></figure>两年前的夏天，一名病人从比利时医院的窗户往外看，在一棵树上发现了一个奇怪的、废弃的塑料和金属丝制成的喜鹊巢。巧合的是，他刚刚在报纸上读到一篇关于一位荷兰生物学家研究用垃圾建造的鸟巢的文章。于是，他匆匆写了一封电子邮件，荷兰生物学家奥克-弗洛里安·希姆斯特拉 (Auke-Florian Hiemstra) 很快就来到了医院的庭院，登上了樱桃采摘机，近距离观察了这个巢穴。<br><br>从这个空中有利位置，Hiemstra 注意到，塑料安装的电线实际上是防鸟尖刺——他后来数了一下，至少有 1,500 根——编织在一起形成了一个“堡垒”。医院安装了这样的尖刺，以防止在屋顶上着陆，但在最靠近巢穴的区域，它们却失踪了。只剩下曾经将钉子固定到位的胶水的残余物，就好像有人——某<em>只鸟</em>——把它们夺走了。希姆斯特拉以前曾在鸟巢中发现过一些令人惊讶的东西：避孕套、口罩、可卡因纸包装、挡风玻璃雨刷片。但这确实是最奇怪的。用防鸟钉做成的鸟巢？ “这听起来基本上就像一个笑话，”他告诉我。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/1886/09/confessions-of-a-birds-nest-hunter/633955/">1886年9月起：一位燕窝猎人的自白</a><br><br>更重要的是，喜鹊巢的尖刺向外排列，仿佛是为了吓跑其他鸟类。这个巢穴的主人是否真的为自己重新利用了我们的防鸟防御系统？喜鹊确实经常收集带刺的树枝，甚至把它们从树上折下来，以保护它们的大巢免受捕食者的侵害。 “在城市环境中，没有那么多带刺的树枝。或者至少有一个很好的替代品——即防鸟钉。”博士希姆斯特拉推测道。荷兰莱顿 Naturalis 生物多样性中心的候选人。为了赶走讨厌的鸟类，我们可能为某个物种提供了一种新颖的防御手段。<br><br>希姆斯特拉（Hiemstra）的大卷发光环就像一个鸟巢，她开始热切地与生物学家朋友们分享这一发现。此后不久，一名树木维护工人联系了其中一个，发现<em>另一个</em>用防鸟钉制成的巢穴，这次是乌鸦在距离鹿特丹莱顿不远的一棵树上筑的。 （相比之下，这个巢穴的尖刺朝内，因此乌鸦不太可能也利用它们进行防御。）然后，在苏格兰格拉斯哥出现了另一个顶部尖刺的喜鹊巢。第三个是在荷兰恩斯赫德。 “越来越多的人不断涌现，”希姆斯特拉告诉我。他说，哪里有防鸟刺，哪里有乌鸦和喜鹊，就可能有更多的防刺巢等待被发现。这个乍一看很不寻常的发现也许其实并不那么不寻常。科学家们<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.hetnatuurhistorisch.nl/fileadmin/user_upload/documents-nmr/Publicaties/Deinsea/Deinsea_21/Deinsea_21_17_25_2023_Hiemstra_et_al.pdf">才刚刚开始关注</a>。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2021/11/birds-nest-feathers-crime-scene/620711/">阅读：没有鸟愿意生活在谋杀巢穴中</a><br><br>许多其他人造材料最终进入了鸟巢。希姆斯特拉（Hiemstra）在跟踪一只携带一块塑料到巢穴的傻瓜后开始研究这种现象。鸟类学家蒂姆·伯克海德（Tim Birkhead）写了一本关于喜鹊的书，他通过电子邮件告诉我，他在英国谢菲尔德看到了由金属丝制成的喜鹊巢。最近一篇关于为什么一些鸟类使用“人为材料”的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://royalsocietypublishing.org/doi/epdf/10.1098/rstb.2022.0156">评论</a>指出，在除南极洲以外的每个大陆 176 种不同物种的巢穴中都发现了垃圾。 “我们对有多少物种使用人造材料感到惊讶，”威尔士班戈大学鸟类学家马克·梅因沃林 (Mark Mainwaring) 说，他是这篇评论的合著者。他的合著者、英国伯明翰大学的鸟类学家吉姆·雷诺兹补充道，鸟类的适应能力很强。 “如果附近有筑巢材料，为什么鸟类还要长途跋涉去寻找筑巢材料呢？”这些充满人造材料的巢穴提醒人们，人类如何彻底改变了鸟类的栖息地：我们清除了它们的本土植物，用塑料垃圾覆盖它们，甚至用敌意的尖刺覆盖它们。<br><br>然而，到目前为止，科学家们还隐约意识到鸟类与那些旨在将它们赶走的物体进行了多少互动。希姆斯特拉在已发表的文献中找不到太多相关内容。但当他接触更大的互联网时，他发现了大量病毒视频和庆祝鸟类胜利的文章：众所周知， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2019/jul/05/chick-flick-cockatoo-gives-anti-nesting-spikes-the-bird-in-viral-video">凤头鹦鹉</a>也会从建筑物上撕下尖刺；游隼将猎物的剩菜串在尖刺上以备后用；在澳大利亚，一只被称为“帕克代尔鸽子”的鸟因为顽固地在防鸟钉上筑巢而获得了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.broadsheet.com.au/melbourne/city-file/article/face-adversity-saga-parkdale-pigeon">民间英雄的地位</a>。鸟类远非仅仅被我们的尖刺所吓倒，它们还改变了用途、重复利用并进行了抵抗。希姆斯特拉沉思道，也许使用更强的胶水将尖刺固定在适当的位置是可能的，但他不想给人类带来任何想法：“我绝对为鸟儿欢呼。”<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 15 Jul 2023 00:47:09 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/07/anti-bird-spikes-nest-magpies/674715/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/07/anti-bird-spikes-nest-magpies/674715/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Russia Has a New Gulag]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>莫斯科恢复了苏联时代的劳改营。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/H1TZce-E-6m-ZKob-s31lEruE4c=/0x0:8867x4988/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/AP23192663533575/original.jpg" alt="乌克兰伊齐乌姆的一间牢房" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>叶夫根尼·马洛莱特卡/美联社</figcaption></figure>1978年，博赫丹·克林查克离开苏联，前往伊朗寻求政治庇护。克林恰克是乌克兰人，出生在利沃夫附近。 1949 年，在他的兄弟作为“乌克兰民族主义者”被捕后，他的家人被驱逐到俄罗斯远东地区的哈巴罗夫斯克。 1957年，克林恰克本人因“反苏煽动”被捕；即使在被释放后，他仍然<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://museum.khpg.org/1142682865">受到持续的监视</a>。在越过边境逃亡并被伊朗人送回后，克林恰克最终被关进了一个名为 Perm-36 的集中营，这是苏联最后的大型政治监狱之一。作为最后一批苏联政治犯之一，他一直呆在那里直到 1990 年。<br><br>克林查克获释后的三十年里，发生了很多事情。 Perm-36 成为一座蓬勃发展的博物馆和纪念场所，每年接待数以万计的游客，其中包括成群结队的学童。 2014年，又被关闭。俄罗斯前囚犯和历史学家出版了古拉格回忆录和历史，举办了会议，举办了展览，制作了纪录片。然后，在过去的几年里， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2021/12/putins-plot-against-russias-future/620930/">他们的组织被取缔</a>，他们的领导人被流放或忽视。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/06/ukraine-russia-war-consequences/673792/">阅读：战争及其后果</a><br><br>如今，同一古拉格系统的新版本正在重建，特别是对于乌克兰人。记者、战争罪调查人员和清算项目等专门团体<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/02/russia-ukraine-war-potemkin-occupation-murder-torture/672841/">已经记录了</a>俄罗斯占领下的乌克兰领土上发生的逮捕、谋杀、监狱和酷刑室事件。慢慢地，人们越来越清楚，这些不仅仅是针对乌克兰抵抗的临时反应。它们是长期计划的一部分：建造一个庞大的营地和惩罚殖民地系统——一个新的古拉格。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://apnews.com/article/ukraine-russia-prisons-civilians-torture-detainees-88b4abf2efbf383272eed9378be13c72">美联社</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://apnews.com/article/ukraine-russia-prisons-civilians-torture-detainees-88b4abf2efbf383272eed9378be13c72">昨天</a>报道称，有证据表明俄罗斯和白俄罗斯至少有 40 个战俘营，以及被占领的乌克兰有 63 个正式和非正式监狱，关押着大约 10,000 名乌克兰人。其中一些是战俘：俄罗斯监狱监测组织 Gulagu.net<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://gulagu.net/cases/voyna-v-ukraine">有证据表明</a>，俄罗斯监狱中的乌克兰士兵没有适当的证件或战俘身份。但大多数乌克兰囚犯是在被占领土被捕或绑架的平民。<br><br>正如古拉格在鼎盛时期一样，奴隶劳动是这些集中营的目的之一。一些被囚禁的乌克兰人被迫为俄罗斯士兵挖战壕、修建防御工事，并挖掘乱葬坑。古拉格的设计目的还在于向更广泛的人群灌输恐惧，新的集中营系统也是如此。平民会因为一些轻微的罪行而被监禁和遭受酷刑——美联社援引了在自行车上系一条乌克兰颜色的丝带为例——或者有时根本没有任何理由。 “清算项目”收集了许多俄罗斯士兵变得偏执并审问普通人（其中许多人是民间组织的志愿者）的例子，询问他们与乌克兰安全部门、中央情报局，甚至乔治·索罗斯的开放社会基金会的联系。美联社描述了一名来自乌克兰扎波罗热地区的平民俘虏，她被从牢房中拉出来，开车绕城一周，并被告知要识别亲乌克兰的人。 1937-38 年大清洗时期，苏联秘密警察同样偏执、同样恐惧，不仅对普通民众，而且对彼此也同样如此。最近的内讧表明，俄罗斯军队在被占领的乌克兰也可能达到这一阶段。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/06/counteroffensive-ukraine-zelensky-crimea/673781/">摘自2023年6月号：反攻</a><br><br>与苏联古拉格集中营一样，新的俄罗斯营地网络也不是暂时的，除非乌克兰人能够收回自己的领土，否则它将会扩大。美联社获得了今年 1 月的一份俄罗斯文件，其中描述了到 2026 年在被占领的乌克兰领土上建造 25 个新监狱和 6 个拘留中心的计划。与苏联古拉格一样，这个系统混乱且无法无天。人们未经审判就被定罪。他们的文件已丢失。有时他们会无缘无故地被保留，或者无缘无故地被释放。他们的亲属没有收到有关他们的任何信息，也无法找到或联系他们。最终，他们也可能被迫上前线。这无疑是俄罗斯囚犯的命运，他们中的许多人现在被要求签署动员文件，如果拒绝，就会遭到殴打和酷刑。与过去一样，俄罗斯监狱长似乎<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.svoboda.org/a/32502251.html">获得了配额</a>，即他们需要提供的囚犯数量，以实现某些中央计划。<br><br>历史的回响不可能是偶然的。克格勃曾经教导新员工学习该机构的历史，俄罗斯安全部门显然也在做同样的事情：他们正在执行在苏联时期“有效”的镇压政策，将博赫丹·克林恰克和他的兄弟等人关进监狱。但这段历史也解释了乌克兰的反应。任何想知道为什么乌克兰人继续战斗、为什么他们不断要求更多武器、为什么他们对缓慢进展的跨大西洋外交感到沮丧、为什么他们看起来愤怒或“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/opinion/why-zelensky-nato-membership-complaint-is-unreasonable">不合理</a>”的人都应该记住这一点：古拉格应该属于过去。 。现在它属于现在。如果乌克兰人不希望它成为他们未来的一部分，他们将不得不将这些难民营以及管理这些难民营的人从乌克兰土地上撤走。在他们成功之前，任何帮助都是不够的。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 14 Jul 2023 16:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/ Russia-gulag-ukraine/674705/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/ Russia-gulag-ukraine/674705/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[And Just Like That Addresses Its Che Diaz Problem]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在第二季进行到一半的时候，《<em>欲望都市》</em>的重启给这个最令人讨厌的角色带来了意想不到的深度。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/SBHCRiaUlqCALC2hYkKUaZ8KzJc=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/AJLT/original.jpg" alt="切·迪亚兹和米兰达·霍布斯在《就这样》" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>克雷格·布兰肯霍恩 / 马克斯</figcaption></figure>本故事包含<strong>《就这样》</strong>第二季<em><strong>第五集的剧透</strong></em><em><strong>。</strong></em><br><br>没有人穿着哈佛连帽衫看起来像辛西娅·尼克松饰演的严肃律师米兰达·霍布斯在<em>《欲望都市》</em>第一季的一集中那样不舒服。在“已婚猪湾”中，米兰达同意在她公司的年度垒球比赛中相亲。但当一位同事向米兰达介绍她的对象时，她意识到同事们错误地判断了她没有男朋友的原因。米兰达在见到一位名叫西德（乔安娜·阿德勒饰）的完美女人后感到尴尬，她责备她的同事对她的性取向的假设。 “是的，我不是同性恋，”她说。 “天啊，什么时候单身变成了同性恋？”<br><br> 1998 年播出的《已婚猪湾》聚焦于已婚人士与单身人士之间的“冷战”——在一场酝酿已久的冲突中，夫妻们将单身女性视为敌人或怜悯的对象。在米兰达的案例中，她所在公司的合伙人对她作为有伴侣的女同性恋的尊重远远超过作为单身异性恋女性的尊重，这促使她与西德建立虚假的关系。米兰达的老板邀请这对夫妇共进晚餐后，米兰达坦白了这场猜谜游戏，但在电梯下楼时亲吻了西德。 “是的，绝对是直的，”她宣称，西德很快就证实了这一结论。<br><br>自该集播出以来的 25 年里，它已经成为<em>《欲望都市</em>》偶尔会嫉妒的酷儿粉丝的最爱，哪怕只是因为它巨大的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://z-p3.www.instagram.com/p/Cs9Gjxru6PT/">模因潜力</a>。它的部分魅力来自于尼克松现实生活中的浪漫轨迹：这位演员于 2003 年与她的长期男性伴侣分手，并在原剧结束时开始与教育活动家克里斯汀·马里诺尼 (Christine Marinoni) 约会。从那时起，她公开承认自己<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.advocate.com/news/daily-news/2012/01/30/cynthia-nixon-being-bisexual-not-choice#toggle-gdpr">是双性恋</a>，与马里诺尼结婚，并选择公开承认<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thedailybeast.com/shes-here-shes-queer-and-cynthia-nixon-wants-you-to-get-used-to-it">自己是酷儿</a>。甚至<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.them.us/story/sex-and-the-city-reboot-miranda-bisexual">在 2021 年</a><em>《欲望都市》</em>重启的消息得到证实之前，许多酷儿粉丝就希望该剧能够重新审视米兰达垒球比赛中首次提出的可能性。在某些圈子里，米兰达是这部剧中<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.lofficielusa.com/pop-culture/sex-and-the-city-book-miranda-hobbes">最有抱负的人物</a>——是这群人中最冷静的一个，也是最有可能警告她的朋友们把一生都围绕着男人的人。长期以来，她一直在一个节目中<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://variety.com/2022/tv/news/cynthia-nixon-miranda-sex-and-the-city-queer-lesbian-1235281614/">充当酷儿女性的不完美化身</a>，该节目<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2021/01/when-sex-and-the-city-returns-will-it-finally-get-queer-people-right">对酷儿的处理</a>有时会转向<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/missmollymary/status/1678835592325660672">滑稽的</a>冒犯领域。<br><br>在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2021/12/and-just-like-that-review-sex-and-city/620959/"><em>《就这样》</em>的第一季</a>中，这部新剧讲述了<em>《欲望都市》中</em>三位原版人物的故事，现年 50 多岁的米兰达确实得到了她的酷儿故事主线。但对于许多粉丝来说，这段经历是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://medium.com/@allegrahirschman/miranda-was-always-already-queer-5708e198aee0">苦乐参半的</a>——很大程度上是因为爱情兴趣开启了她的觉醒。米兰达仍然与史蒂夫（大卫·艾根伯格饰）保持着婚姻关系，她深深地爱上了非二元的单口喜剧演员切·迪亚兹（萨拉·拉米雷斯饰），切·迪亚兹是一位多角恋、泛性恋的混乱代理人，她共同主持了一个播客<em>《X、Y和我》。</em>描述为涵盖“性别角色、性角色和肉桂卷”。一位<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.tiktok.com/@cbc/video/7253475865772707078">受压抑</a>、成就斐然的律师中年酷儿觉醒的想法一点也不不可思议——她可能会迷恋一位年轻的、吸大麻的煽动者。尽管如此， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nbcnews.com/nbc-out/out-pop-culture/agony-ecstasy-mirandas-coming-sex-city-reboot-rcna13213">切还是很恼火</a>。在他们的第一个场景中，切通过称嘉莉（莎拉·杰西卡·帕克饰）为“卡莉女士”来欢迎他们的两位顺性别共同主持人加入播客。 Cis”介绍自己为“酷儿、非二元性别、墨西哥爱尔兰天后，代表这两种无聊性别之外的所有人”，然后按下音板上的一个按钮，用响亮的“醒来的时刻！”来打断这首歌。<br><br>在萨姆·桑德斯 (Sam Sanders) 的播客<em>《Into It》</em> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://open.spotify.com/episode/3NSBFcZpl5vZRrT5gsqFX7?si=d6159ba252cb47c5&amp;nd=1">最近一集中</a>，该节目的编剧之一萨曼莎·厄比 (Samantha Irby) 将迪亚兹比作“那种将一杯咖啡变成殖民主义教训的人……切就像变成了 12 的那个人。” ”自从珍妮·谢克特（Jenny Schecter）这个令人难以忍受的天真无邪的<em>《拉字至上》</em>中心人物以来，还没有一个虚构的角色让我认识的几乎所有酷儿以及无数陌生人如此彻底地烦恼，他们的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.buzzfeed.com/lyapalater/hey-its-che-diaz-jokes">推文</a>、Instagram 帖子和 TikTok 都出现在我的屏幕上。引用<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thedailybeast.com/obsessed/and-just-like-thats-che-diaz-is-the-worst-character-on-tv"><em>《每日野兽报》</em></a>一篇特别热情的评论：“这样的角色如此令人发指，真是不幸。没有人<em>愿意</em>将系列中唯一的新 LGBTQ+ 角色挑为最差的。然而切·迪亚兹让我们别无选择。”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/06/and-just-like-that-season-2-review/674474/">阅读：曾经定义时代的演出的幽灵</a><br><br>然后，我惊讶地发现自己在最新一集中对切产生<em>了类似同情的</em>感觉。第一季结束时， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2022/02/and-just-like-finale-miranda-che/621487/">米兰达一反常态地离开了</a>史蒂夫、她的朋友们，以及一个重要的职业机会，跟随切去了洛杉矶，这位喜剧演员希望在那里为他们的半自传式成长情景喜剧的试播集开绿灯。 。切在第一季中很容易成为模仿的对象，而第二季则清楚地表明， <em>《就这样》</em>编剧室并不是漫无目的地从网络社会正义术语中拉出来的。从周四播出的第五集开始，该剧增加了切的深度——这是一个值得欢迎的转变，也为米兰达创造了更多的空间来解决她在想象未来成为切的住家拉拉队长时所面临的一些存在主义问题。<br><br>在由 Irby 和 Lucas Froehlich 共同编剧的这一集中，Che 观看了纽约焦点小组对他们的节目<em>《Che Pasa》</em>试播集的试映反馈。该团体中的一名年轻有色人种酷儿成员对以切为原型的角色提出了质疑，称他们的故事情节是“虚假的、经过净化的、表演性的、俗气的、老爸笑话、非二元体验的狗屎版本。 ” （“这很糟糕，”他们补充道。）这些批评立即让切落泪，粉碎了他们对定义人生的工作意义的信念。当米兰达后来试图安慰他们说受访者不知道他们在说什么时，切拒绝了她：“一个来自布鲁克林的性别酷儿把它搞砸了！电话是从屋内传来的。”<br><br>切本可以直接回应现实生活中观众对他们的抱怨，但这种交流之所以有效，是因为它让我们看到了从漫画中出现真实<em>角色</em>的潜力。任何类型的艺术创作都是一个极其脆弱的过程，当作品是自传体时更是如此。对于酷儿和跨性别者，尤其是有色人种来说，在好莱坞取得重大突破往往意味着要应对该行业令人筋疲力尽的结构性障碍和对容易消除的刻板印象的偏好。这种类型的反馈可能会令人士气低落，但这是预料之中的。然而，社区内部的判断力受到的打击要大得多，这使得切受到的批评尤其具有毁灭性。 “我花了 46 年才弄清楚我是谁，”切告诉米兰达，“然后一个焦点小组花了一个小时就毁了我。”<br><br>到目前为止，让切如此令人抓狂的部分原因在于，这部剧本身似乎不确定自己的角色是谁，以及她们在三位核心女性的故事中扮演什么角色。在第一季中，切是嘉莉的年轻陪衬，嘉莉在播客中扮演切的正经异性恋对手，因为她对关于酷儿的数字笑话和有关性的问题感到不舒服。夏洛特（克里斯汀·戴维斯饰）并没有真正与切互动，只是质疑为什么米兰达<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nbcnews.com/nbc-out/out-pop-culture/agony-ecstasy-mirandas-coming-sex-city-reboot-rcna13213">几乎在一夜之间</a>就毁掉了她与史蒂夫的关系。切的存在，似乎不仅仅是为了向米兰达表明她在婚姻中并不幸福，也是为了让三人了解他们的特权——作为<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2021/12/24/arts/television/sex-and-the-city-girls-girlfriends-run-the-world.html">对原版<em>《欲望都市》</em>的纠正，</a>同时扩展新系列所描绘的生活类型。 。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2022/02/and-just-like-finale-miranda-che/621487/">阅读：我们需要谈谈米兰达</a><br><br>对于一个角色来说，需要付出很多努力。非二元人物确实存在于其他节目中，故事情节<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.npr.org/2021/11/18/1056817713/sort-of-hbo-max-review">丰富而复杂</a>，但在<em>《欲望都市》</em>的阴影下，像切这样的角色总是很难被认为是该剧最接近非二元人物的角色。像。在最初的竞选中，嘉莉曾将双性恋称为“前往同性恋镇途中的中途停留”。 So it&#39;s not hard to see why including a character who identifies as “an equal-opportunity confuser” on the reboot would be seen as an attempt at writing “catnip to … Gen Zers who identify outside of the binary,” as James Factora <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.them.us/story/and-just-like-that-mediocre-nonbinary-representation">wrote for <em>Them</em></a> in 2021.<br><br> Having the Gen X Che reckon with the limits of their story among younger queer people gives <em>And Just Like That</em> viewers the first real sign that the series doesn&#39;t think the comedian actually <em>does</em> stand in for their whole community. On <em>Into It</em> , Irby remarked that Che&#39;s pitched-up personality was “intentional.” In Season 2, though, “the artifice of Che starts to crumble.” We see that clearly in Irby and Froehlich&#39;s episode, but it continues throughout the next two episodes too. Without spoiling anything, Che&#39;s search for meaning brings them closer to Carrie, and pushes Miranda to explore her queerness with depth and curiosity rather than with <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.salon.com/2023/07/09/and-just-like-that-miranda-che/">awkward, selfish impulsivity</a> .<br><br> By the seventh episode of the season, <em>And Just Like That</em> comes closer to fulfilling fans&#39; hopes for this new canonically queer Miranda, even if it hasn&#39;t quite reconciled her with the Miranda who recoiled from kissing Syd. Steve gets more space for his own complicated reactions to Miranda&#39;s journey, and to the dissolution of their <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thecut.com/2022/01/sex-and-the-citys-steve-deserves-better.html">beloved</a> , if <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://graziamagazine.com/us/articles/reconsidering-miranda-steve-sex-and-the-city/">sometimes rocky</a> , union. And Che, surprisingly, carves out a role in the troupe that feels more fleshed out than that of either the real-estate baddie Seema (Sarita Choudhury) or Miranda&#39;s graduate-school professor turned roommate, Nya (Karen Pittman). Thank goodness for that, because I&#39;m not sure I could handle even one more “WOKE MOMENT!”<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 14 Jul 2023 14:37:49 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/and-just-like-that-che-diaz-character/674703/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/and-just-like-that-che-diaz-character/674703/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Fundraising Stunts Are Getting Out of Control]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> A rule passed to make sure Republican politicians have broad support is instead making them more creative about fundraising. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/Ezy9T4wPaLGEa1kldyzDkEA4s9Q=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/doug_burgum/original.jpg" alt="道格·布尔古姆" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Dan Koeck / Reuters</figcaption></figure> You don&#39;t become a billionaire without being clever with money, but Doug Burgum&#39;s latest scheme is a head-scratcher: The North Dakota governor <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://secure.winred.com/doug-burgum-for-america/gift-card-nd/?amount=1&amp;utm_medium=sms_hf&amp;utm_source=ds_na_nd&amp;utm_campaign=20230710_gift-card-send-nd_generic_burgumforpresident&amp;utm_content=donate_cpyrs&amp;exitintent=true">is offering $20 gift cards</a> to people who donate one greenback dollar to his presidential campaign. His fellow candidate Vivek Ramaswamy is <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=t8EiUSyuWqI">offering a 10 percent commission</a> to anyone who brings in donations. A super PAC supporting Miami Mayor Francis Suarez is <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.francisfreecollege.com/">offering one donor a year of free college tuition</a> .<br><br> Critics have long pointed out how big money distorts politics, but these fundraising stunts demonstrate how now even small money has come to warp campaigns. These GOP candidates are trying to reach a Republican National Committee threshold of 40,000 individual donors, including 200 each in 20 states or territories, to qualify for primary debates. The RNC has set a high bar to make sure that candidates have real support—and perhaps to downplay the influence of major donors. But the effect may be the opposite: enticing candidates to try novel tactics to create the illusion of real support, because they know that getting on the debate stage is essential for remaining viable and attracting those big donors. As the old saying goes, it takes money to make money.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2016/10/campaign-finance-fundraising-citizens-united/504425/">Read: Small donors still aren&#39;t as important as wealthy ones</a><br><br> These tactics are the product of a new focus in politics on small-dollar donors, which means that they have not been legally tested. “The whole time I was at the FEC I never saw anything like this,” Ann Ravel, a former chair of the Federal Election Commission, told me. Although she called the moves “quite unseemly,” she said she doubted that they clearly broke existing statutes or regulations. But other experts believe that Burgum&#39;s scheme may fall afoul of the law, even if the others are allowed.<br><br> An early forerunner of these plans came in 2020, when the Democratic presidential candidate Andrew Yang announced a plan to give away $120,000—$10,000 a month for one year to 10 families, drawn randomly from people who signed up on his website. The idea was to advertise Yang&#39;s proposal for universal basic income for all Americans. (Ravel, for her part, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2019/09/21/andrew-yang-giveaway-campaign-finance-fec-228150/">wrote an op-ed at the time</a> arguing that plan was likely illegal.) This year&#39;s schemes eschew such a connection to policy and, unlike Yang&#39;s, require that citizens contribute money, not just enter their email.<br><br> Under Ramaswamy&#39;s plan, anyone can gather donations and take a small cut. In a video, he called it a way to “democratize” the old system and break up the “oligopoly” of traditional fundraising. A better way to describe it would be as Uber, but for campaign finance. Candidates have long paid professional fundraisers to bring in cash. They have also relied on “bundlers,” who persuade friends and acquaintances to give, even though each donor is limited to $3,300 in individual federal donations this cycle. Ramaswamy is basically combining those and applying them to small donations.<br><br> Rather than let anyone take a small cut, SOS America PAC is effectively holding a raffle for one big winner. They&#39;re asking people to give to Suarez&#39;s campaign, and they&#39;ll give away a tuition gift to one contributor. You&#39;ll have to shop around if you win, though: With a $15,000 limit, a Floridian could cover a full year at the University of Florida, Florida State, or Florida International (Suarez&#39;s alma mater), but an out-of-state student would be able to cover only part of the cost. (That sum would barely reach a quarter of the cost at the University of Miami.)<br><br> Burgum&#39;s approach is the most novel. Campaigns commonly offer swag for donations—write a check, get a bumper sticker—but handing out gift cards goes a step further. It sounds like it ought to somehow be illegal. But is it? Candidates aren&#39;t permitted to buy votes, but giving a dollar doesn&#39;t obligate anyone to actually vote for Burgum. They could just be involved in a neat arbitrage and vote for someone else. Federal law also bans “straw donations”: You can&#39;t give money to your friend or spouse or employee and ask them to donate it. The ban serves two purposes. First, it prevents individuals from circumventing the individual contribution limit; second, it ensures compliance with donor-disclosure laws.<br><br> But Burgum isn&#39;t subject to contribution limits, because candidates are allowed to give unlimited amounts to their own campaigns, and the scheme obviously doesn&#39;t violate disclosure requirements. “The statutes and regulations are not clear enough to indicate that there&#39;s any real legal problem with this activity,” Ravel told me.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2019/07/campaign-finance-supreme-court/594751/">Richard L. Hasen: Unlimited contributions to candidates, coming soon?</a><br><br> Other experts are not so sure. “I do not fault anyone for thinking creatively about lawful ways to raise money,” <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.paulsryan.com/">Paul S. Ryan</a> , a longtime campaign-finance lawyer, told me. Yet he believes that giving the gift cards and accepting the donations violate the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/52/30122">plain language of the straw-donor law</a> : “No person shall make a contribution in the name of another person or knowingly permit his name to be used to effect such a contribution, and no person shall knowingly accept a contribution made by one person in the name of another person.” He worries that if Burgum is allowed to use the scheme, it will set a “horrible precedent,” where a candidate might use the same method to solicit larger donations, or enlist a wealthy friend.<br><br> The RNC is arguably also a victim of the arrangement. “Burgum is trying to defraud the RNC,” Ryan said. “These aren&#39;t unique individual donors; these are fake straw donors. If I were at the RNC I would not accept these donors, because they&#39;re illegitimate.”<br><br> A Burgum spokesperson did not immediately respond to a request for comment, nor did an RNC spokesperson. The FEC doesn&#39;t comment on specific cases, and in any event the body&#39;s <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2013/07/this-is-why-we-cant-have-nice-elections-the-dysfunctional-fec/277639/">structure and partisan makeup</a> mean that it has deadlocked on most important issues over the past few years. Ravel was skeptical that the body would enforce any violations even if they exist in these cases.<br><br> The argument for grassroots donors is not as simple as it might appear on the surface. As David Byler of <em>The Washington Post</em> has written, small-dollar contributions <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2023/05/01/small-donors-political-campaign-spending/">have driven polarization</a> . But if the goal of donor requirements is to increase the power of small donors, a $20-for-$1 exchange actually does the opposite, increasing the power of one massively wealthy candidate to game the system.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 14 Jul 2023 14:16:48 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/doug-burgum-fundraising-stunt-campaign/674697/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/doug-burgum-fundraising-stunt-campaign/674697/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[China Doesn’t Want to Compete. It Wants to Win.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> A recent flurry of diplomatic talks shouldn&#39;t be taken to mean that Beijing is looking for compromise with Washington. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/fEVteJ87Gyxk0ujHb2YcieqYVE8=/0x0:5174x2910/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_1258784245_copy/original.jpg" alt="美国国务卿安东尼·布林肯与中国高级外交官王毅交谈" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Leah Millis / Pool / AFP / Getty</figcaption></figure>一群美国高级政策制定者正在前往北京执行外交任务，以修补中美之间破裂的关系。美国气候特使约翰·克里预计将于周日抵达北京，一周前，财政部长珍妮特·耶伦抵达北京。国务卿安东尼·布林肯一个月前访问了这里。经过近一年的紧张沟通后，一系列外交活动是个好消息：如果两国政府能够相互对话，也许他们就不会互相开枪了。<br><br>或者至少是这样的。改善对话是拜登总统试图展示在与中国抗衡时走冲突与绥靖之间的中间道路的可能性。 He believes that the US can and should compete with China while setting in place guardrails that will prevent competition from veering  into confrontation.两国甚至可能找到在气候变化等紧迫的全球问题上进行合作的机会。<br><br>中国领导人习近平似乎很顺从，至少目前如此。事实上，习近平政府急于给耶伦的访问描绘积极的一面，以至于把事情说得有点厚重。 Referring to a rainbow that appeared over Beijing upon Yellen&#39;s arrival, Premier Li Qiang <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.globaltimes.cn/page/202307/1293956.shtml">told</a> Yellen that the US and China can see “more rainbows” after a period of “wind and rain.”随着中国经济严重陷入困境，美国及其盟国开始“去风险”或减少对中国的依赖，习近平和他的团队似乎有心情聊天、魅力和改变想法。<br><br>但这些努力不应被视为习近平接受拜登的两国关系双轨模式。相反，习近平的看法似乎恰恰相反：绅士式竞争是行不通的，华盛顿必须要么屈服于北京的意愿，要么准备一决胜负。习近平最终如何回应拜登，可能会决定冷战式的大国竞争时代（这已经够糟糕了）和对每个人来说都是灾难性的热战。<br><br> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/06/china-economy-xi-jinping-us-relationship-investment-trade/674321/">Read: China and the West are coming apart. Can China&#39;s economy continue to rise?</a><br><br>美国外交政策制定者常常认为自己在美国与其他国家的关系中处于主导地位，其他国家政府的政策在很大程度上是对华盛顿政策的反应。显然，任何国家的外交政策都会在一定程度上对其他国家做出反应——包括中国。但国家领导人也有自己的议程和目标，这些议程和目标与华盛顿做出的具体决定和采取的行动几乎没有关系。<br><br>习近平肯定有自己的议程，而且他毫不掩饰这一点。 Since taking power more than a decade ago, he has <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-10-18/full-text-of-xi-jinping-s-speech-at-china-20th-party-congress-2022?sref=BGQFqz7X">stated</a> his goal of achieving the “Chinese Dream” of “national rejuvenation,” which means the resurrection of China&#39;s greatness on the world stage.正如共产党所说，要实现这一目标，就需要根据北京对其合法边界的定义，与台湾实现国家统一。 Xi has <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://apnews.com/article/china-us-military-taiwan-xi-jinping-14f9c3d8fef26779f017d927aa352eeb">pledged</a> to build China a “world-class” military to give heft to his foreign-policy aims.他的政府还宣布计划利用国家支持来主导新兴技术，包括电动汽车和人工智能。最近，习近平概述了他对新世界秩序的愿景，该秩序将剥夺国际事务中的自由主义价值观，并提升威权政府的合法性。<br><br>在整个任期内，习近平坚定地追求这些目标，很少考虑华盛顿的意见。自奥巴马政府以来，他一直无视华盛顿对他对几乎整个南中国海提出主权主张的反对，包括在人造岛屿上建立军事设施。华盛顿进一步明确表示，它认为习近平的产业政策向高科技行业提供大量国家财政支持，对美国企业不公平且构成威胁。但习近平只是继续花钱。 More recently, Xi has brushed off US concerns about his support for Russian President Vladimir Putin and has continued to deepen ties with Moscow.<br><br>习近平已表示，他无意为了改善与美国的关系而改变政策。相反，北京的一贯立场是，华盛顿应对紧张局势升级承担全部责任，因此修复紧张局势完全是美国的责任。 “If the United States does not hit the brake but continues to speed down the wrong path,” Qin Gang, China&#39;s foreign minister, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.fmprc.gov.cn/eng/wjdt_665385/zyjh_665391/202303/t20230307_11037190.html">said</a> in March, “there will surely be conflict and confrontation.”<br><br> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2015/09/xi-jinping-china-book-chinese-dream/406387/">Read: The world according to Xi Jinping</a><br><br> After Blinken&#39;s visit last month, Xinhua, China&#39;s official news agency, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://en.people.cn/n3/2023/0621/c90000-20034114.html">published</a> an editorial that suggested “three R words that Washington should remember: rationality, responsibility and results.”文章还称，“中美关系急转直下的根本原因是华盛顿对中国的误解，导致了错误的对华政策”。即使在耶伦会议的影响下，北京仍继续向华盛顿施压，要求其做出让步，但没有提供任何回报。 After Yellen&#39;s departure, China&#39;s finance ministry issued a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reuters.com/world/china-urges-practical-us-action-sanctions-after-yellen-talks-2023-07-10/">statement</a> saying that Beijing “requires” the United States to “cease the suppression of Chinese enterprises” and “take concrete steps to respond to China&#39;s major concerns in economic relations” in order to improve ties. Only three days before Yellen arrived, Xi&#39;s <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reuters.com/technology/us-firm-axt-applying-permits-after-china-restricts-chipmaking-exports-2023-07-04/">government</a> announced its own export controls on two key metals used in electronics manufacturing—hardly an olive branch.<br><br>习近平真正想要的是行动自由，不受美国权力、规则或批评的束缚。他的许多政策旨在消除中国在美国惩罚性行动面前的脆弱性。他的军事建设是专门为了对抗美国武装部队投送力量的方式而设计的。 Xi&#39;s <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.scmp.com/tech/policy/article/3222599/tech-war-chinese-leader-xi-jinping-called-tech-self-sufficiency-decade-ago-according-speech-new-book">drive</a> for economic “self-sufficiency,” especially in crucial technologies such as semiconductors, is meant to protect China from Washington&#39;s sanctions. When Xi told Blinken that “major-country competition does not represent the trend of the times” in their June meeting, according to the Chinese <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.fmprc.gov.cn/mfa_eng/zxxx_662805/202306/t20230619_11099957.html">summary</a> of the talk, he might have meant that he desires peaceful relations with the United States, but he could just as easily have been saying he doesn&#39;t think he should have to contend with the United States as an impediment to his volition.<br><br>北京和华盛顿对“竞争”的看法根本不同。华盛顿一再试图将去年实施的限制向中国出口某些芯片技术等措施描述为捍卫美国国家安全的有针对性的努力，而不是为了破坏中国的发展。但在北京，这些举措被视为只不过是一个全球超级大国利用其经济杠杆来维持其主导地位。 Qin Gang once <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-04-04/us-says-tough-china-moves-needed-to-counter-national-champions?sref=BGQFqz7X">said</a> that Biden&#39;s “so-called competition means to contain and suppress China in all respects.”<br><br>习近平可能在闭门谈判中表现出比公开谈判更大的灵活性。中国的大部分言论都是针对国内受众，让习近平看起来像是中国国家利益的坚定捍卫者。 Yet Xi has <a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/special/2021-07/01/c_1310038244.htm">called</a> China&#39;s rise an “inevitability,” and he could assume that the United States (and everybody else) will eventually have to concede to China, whether they like it or not.<br><br>北京的态度让人怀疑，通过对话，甚至是许多美国评论人士所敦促的那种更温和的对华政策，到底能取得多大成果。 Writing <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.union-bulletin.com/opinion/opinion_columns/commentary-stabilize-us-china-relations-before-a-near-miss-turns-into-a-crisis/article_fe0a8178-0acb-11ee-93b4-a37444bcf98e.html">recently</a> about tensions over Taiwan, Michael Swaine, a senior research fellow at the Quincy Institute for Responsible Statecraft, rightfully worried about the “&#39;tit-for-tat&#39; dynamic that has come to define US and Chinese interactions, whereby each side doubles down on what it sees as deterrence signals that in fact only serve to provoke further such signals.”他建议两国采取措施化解可能的危机，包括华盛顿通过减少在敏感的台湾海峡的海军过境来显示诚意。 The former AIG chair Maurice Greenberg, representing a group of concerned American business leaders and policy makers, argued last year that the US should build on the positive benefits of the two countries&#39; economic relationship to create a more constructive dialogue: “It is in our national interest, now more than ever, to do all we can to improve US-China relations,” he <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/we-want-to-rebuild-us-china-relations-trade-business-economic-growth-antony-blinken-foreign-policy-11657141306">wrote</a> .<br><br>但这些做法是否真正有利于双边关系，最终取决于习近平是否愿意做出同样的回应。到目前为止，中国领导人对改变政策以适应华盛顿的兴趣不大。他目前与拜登政府的接触很可能只不过是一次钓鱼探险，看看他能通过一些微笑和握手而不改变他的议程来获得什么好处。习近平发出的更加一致的信号表明，与中国相处的唯一出路就是向中国让步。<br><br>这并不意味着对话毫无意义。如果（或者更有可能的是，当）危机爆发时，开放的沟通渠道可以帮助避免灾难。但彩虹尽头很可能没有一桶金在等待。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 14 Jul 2023 14:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/07/-us-china-economic-agenda-competition/674694/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/07/-us-china-economic-agenda-competition/674694/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Drink More Water]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The dos and don&#39;ts of hydrating in a heat wave <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/kUl52UotDYjprRiWwOsW33o81Vk=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/survive_a_heatwave_horz_final/original.jpg" alt="水滴和水杯的拼贴画" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Illustration by The Atlantic. Sources: Getty.</figcaption></figure> The heat—miserable and oppressive—is not abating. Today, a third of Americans are under a heat alert as temperatures keep breaking records: Phoenix has hit 110 degrees Fahrenheit <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/11/us/phoenix-heat-wave.html">for two weeks straight</a> , while this weekend Death Valley in California <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/13/us/california-heat-wave.html">could surpass</a> the all-time high of 130 degrees.<br><br> Even less extreme heat than that can be dangerous. Recently, in Texas, Louisiana, part of Arizona, and Florida, there have been <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://apnews.com/article/heat-deaths-dome-texas-california-south-d820a8782d3bc15abbe713af81dc7d7f">reports</a> of <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.12news.com/article/news/local/hot-temperatures-have-led-to-8-deaths-10-burn-hospitalizations-officials-say-reporting-lags-numbers-will-soar/75-f6367179-0be1-4ced-af85-28c9e4445142">deaths</a> from heat, and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/jun/28/record-setting-texas-heat-sends-hundreds-emergency-rooms">many more</a> hospitalizations. The toll of a heat wave is not always clear in the moment: A <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41591-023-02419-z#Sec8">new report suggests tha</a> <u>t</u> last summer&#39;s historic heat wave in Europe killed more than 60,000 people.<br><br> Ideally, you&#39;d stay in the air-conditioned indoors as much as possible. That&#39;s not an option for everyone. The other thing to do is stay hydrated. The importance of getting enough fluid is hard to overstate—and often underappreciated: Last month, the Texas state legislature banned local governments from mandating water breaks for construction workers. In the heat, hydration “impacts everything,” Stavros Kavouras, the director of the Hydration Science Lab at Arizona State University, in Phoenix, told me. And with temperatures continuing to rise, it&#39;s essential to get it right.<br><br> Serious dehydration is really, really bad for you. Your blood volume decreases, which makes your heart work less effectively. “Your ability to thermoregulate declines,” Kavouras told me, “so your body temperature is getting higher and higher.” You might feel weak or dizzy. Your heart rate rises; it gets harder to focus. The worst-case scenario is heatstroke, when your body stops being able to cool itself—a  potentially fatal medical emergency.<br><br> In extreme temperatures, heat injuries can happen quicker than you might think. Given that the human body is mostly water, you might assume that there is some to spare, but inconveniently, this is not the case. “If you lose even 10 percent of [the water] your body has, you are entering the zone of serious clinical dehydration,” Kavouras said. “And if you look at <em>optimal</em> health, even losing just 1 percent of your body weight impacts your ability to function.” There are two basic ways your body cools itself when it gets hot. One is to send more blood to the skin, which releases heat from the core of your body, and is the reason you turn red when you&#39;re overheated. The other is to sweat. It evaporates off your body, and in the process, your body loses excess heat. You can&#39;t cool yourself as effectively if you&#39;re not properly hydrated. At the same time, one of your main cooling mechanisms is actively dehydrating, which means the goal is not just to <em>be</em> hydrated, but to stay that way.<br><br> What that takes depends on many factors rather than a single universal rule, but in general, the danger zone is “high humidity with anything above 90 degrees,” Kavouras said, at which point, “it&#39;s actually dangerous” just to be outside. The more active you are in the heat, and the hotter and more humid it is, the greater the risk—and the more important proper hydration becomes. The standard water target in the US during non-heat-wave times is 3.7 liters a day for men and 2.7 liters for women. When it&#39;s very, very hot out, you need more. Even if you spend most of the day in the bliss of AC, you are almost certainly leaving the house at <em>some</em> point.<br><br> Instead of trying to figure out what that precise amount should be, Kavouras recommends you focus on two things instead. “No. 1, keep water close to you. If you have water close to you, or whatever healthy beverage, you&#39;ll end up drinking more, just because it&#39;s closer,” he said. And second: Keep an eye on how often you pee—pale urine, six to seven times a day, or every two to three hours, is good. You want it to be “basically like a Chablis, a Riesling, Pinot Grigio, or champagne-colored,” John Higgins, a sports cardiologist at McGovern Medical School at UTHealth, in Houston, told me. “If you notice the urine is getting darker, like a Chardonnay- or Sauvignon Blanc–type of thing, that generally means you are dehydrated.”<br><br> Certain groups are especially at risk. Older adults are more prone to dehydration, as are young children, people who are pregnant, and people taking certain medications—blood-pressure medications, for example. None of this requires you to take in <em>extra</em> fluids per se, just that you need to be even more careful that you&#39;re getting enough.<br><br> As for what to drink, as a go-to beverage, straight water is hard to beat. Water with fruit slices floating in it has the benefit of feeling like something from a luxury hotel. Carbonated water is also good—you might not be able to drink quite as much of it, which is a potential drawback, but “there is no mechanism in your GI system that will make sparkling water less effective at hydrating you,” Kavouras said. You probably want to avoid downing giant buckets of coffee—caffeine is a diuretic in large quantities and Higgins warns against sugary drinks for the same reason. (A daily iced coffee is fine.) If you&#39;re doing hours of heavy sweating, then you might work in some (less sugary) sports drinks. But for the majority of people, water remains the ideal. Food can also be a fluid source: “Make sure you&#39;re eating a diet that&#39;s rich in vegetables and fruits that have water content,” William Adams, the director of the University of North Carolina at Greensboro&#39;s Hydration, Environment and Thermal (HEAT) Stress Lab, advised. Alcohol, which causes you to <em>lose</em> fluid, is definitively unhelpful.<br><br> There are lots of water myths out there. Can you go too hard? Technically, it&#39;s possible to over-hydrate, causing an electrolyte imbalance, but all three experts agreed that for most people, this isn&#39;t really a concern. You can find <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.npr.org/sections/thesalt/2012/07/11/156378713/cool-down-with-a-hot-drink-its-not-as-crazy-as-you-think">arguments</a> for drinking hot drinks in the summer—the idea being that they increase the amount you sweat, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.smithsonianmag.com/science-nature/a-hot-drink-on-a-hot-day-can-cool-you-down-1338875/">thereby promoting cooling</a> . But Kavouras is emphatic that you&#39;re better off with cold drinks, which cool your body, he said. In the moments before a race, marathon runners will sometimes take it one step further, slurping ice slurries to lower their body temperature. For good old-fashioned drinking water, about <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.researchgate.net/publication/261517517_Optimal_Composition_of_Fluid-Replacement_Beverages">50 degrees Fahrenheit</a> is best—roughly the temperature of cool water from the tap.<br><br> One final key to staying hydrated: Start early. A lot of people, Higgins said, are lightly dehydrated all the time, heat wave or not. “So particularly when you first wake up in the morning, typically you are in a dehydrated state.” Accordingly, he recommends that people drink about a standard water bottle&#39;s worth—roughly 17 ounces—as soon as they wake up. The other thing people forget about, he said, is what happens when they come back inside after enduring the outdoors. “You keep sweating,” he pointed out. In other words: hydrate, and then <em>keep</em> hydrating.<br><br> As crucial as hydration is, it is not a miracle. “It doesn&#39;t mean that you can say, &#39;I hydrate well, so I&#39;ll go out for a run in the 120-degree weather, and I&#39;ll be fine because I&#39;m drinking a lot,&#39;” Kavouras said. “It doesn&#39;t work this way.” Still, it is a simple but effective tool. As heat waves like this one become even more frequent, many more people will need to learn how to become attuned to their hydration. And perhaps adequate water can be a perverse sort of comfort: You can&#39;t control the unrelenting heat, but you likely can control your water intake. In a heat wave, it helps to have a glass-half-full attitude—and an emptied glass of water.<br><br> <small><em>This story is part of the Atlantic Planet series supported by HHMI&#39;s Science and Educational Media Group.</em></small><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 14 Jul 2023 13:29:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/07/the-dos-and-donts-of-hydrating-in-a-heat-wave/674704/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/07/the-dos-and-donts-of-hydrating-in-a-heat-wave/674704/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Is a Glass of Wine Harmless? Wrong Question.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The latest alcohol advice ignores the value of pleasure. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/LhxMO4yoXcC8qZw70hecla-jF4E=/1x0:2444x1374/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_56464858_copy/original.jpg" alt="一个人检查一杯酒的图像" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Imagno / Getty</figcaption></figure> <small><i data-stringify-type="italic">This article was featured in One Story to Read Today, a newsletter in which our editors recommend a single must-read from</i> The Atlantic <i data-stringify-type="italic">, Monday through Friday.</i> <i data-stringify-type="italic"><a data-event-element="inline link" data-sk="tooltip_parent" data-stringify-link="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" delay="150" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Sign up for it here.</a></i></small><br><br> Not so long ago, alcohol was good for you. In a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://blog.iwfs.org/2014/08/french-paradox-how-a-60-minutes-segment-transformed-red-wine-consumption-in-america/">1991 segment on <i>60 Minutes</i></a> , a French researcher <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=njm1LkXP2sg">claimed</a> that red-wine consumption was responsible for good health in France. This argument proved popular with the wine-consuming public, and prompted academic <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/014067369190542W">papers</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bmj.com/content/310/6988/1165.short">positing</a> an inverse relationship between red-wine consumption and cardiovascular disease. Scientists even put forward a mechanistic theory for why red wine was healthy, involving a compound <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://europepmc.org/article/med/7499059">called resveratrol</a> .<br><br> Others soon cast doubt on the possibility that red wine could really have any causal relationship with longevity. The “alcohol is good for you” narrative eroded and, in the past year, seems to have fully collapsed. A number of researchers are now arguing that basically <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://time.com/5376552/how-much-alcohol-to-drink-study/"><i>any</i> amount</a> of alcohol is bad for you; a <i>New York Times</i> article from January was titled “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/01/13/well/mind/alcohol-health-effects.html">Even a Little Alcohol Can Harm Your Health</a> .” Some— <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://ccsa.ca/canadas-guidance-alcohol-and-health">including the Canadian government</a> —are suggesting that, as a result, the safest choice is not to drink <i>at all</i> .<br><br> Excessive alcohol consumption clearly leads to significant problems, physical and emotional. That is not up for debate. However: <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DkS1pkKpILY">Recent</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/wellness/2023/03/31/moderate-drinking-alcohol-wine-risks/">rhetoric</a> , veering in the direction of abstinence, goes well beyond the sound advice to avoid heavy drinking and ignores the value of pleasure.<br><br> <a href="http://v/">Read: A daily drink is almost certainly not going to hurt you</a><br><br> A pleasure-agnostic approach to health advice is now in vogue even outside the domain of alcohol, and is filtering down to the general public with sometimes absurd results. Recently, a reader asked me: <i>Is there any data on health benefits to orgasms?</i> I am not aware of reliable data from randomized experiments suggesting that having more orgasms improves health. That isn&#39;t the point of orgasms, anyway. The point of orgasms is that they are fun. We do not need to prove health benefits to want to have them.<br><br> Public-health advice is sometimes based on a “lexicographic” standard—putting the effects on health first, second, and third, and ignoring other considerations, including enjoyment. A lexicographic standard applied to, say, meat consumption would hold that we must always eat burgers well done, because that is the best way to avoid any risk of <i>E. coli</i> , even though well-done burgers are tasteless. More generally, some in public health avoid discussing the negative unintended consequences of absolutism. During the coronavirus pandemic, some officials advocated strongly for long-lasting school closures, arguing that keeping kids at home was the only way to prevent in-school spread among students and teachers. That was, in a technical sense, true, but this recommendation failed to consider the enormous costs to children of those closures, which should have been weighed against any benefits.<br><br> Coming back to alcohol, pleasure-agnosticism could make sense if the best available evidence indicated <i>substantial</i> harm from even moderate drinking. It does not. I should also stress that the data are fundamentally flawed because the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-022-28735-5">largest</a> , most commonly cited studies we have are observational, not randomized. And the characteristics of people who consume alcohol in moderation are different from those who do not.<br><br> In 2018, <i>The Lancet</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thelancet.com/article/S0140-6736(18)31310-2/fulltext">published a comprehensive study</a> on the link between alcohol consumption and cancer, heart disease, and other illnesses. It is an extraordinary work of scholarship, combining hundreds of previous papers. And the results indicate an upward trend in cancer, in particular, as alcohol consumption increases. But the effects at moderate levels of drinking—say, one to two drinks a day— <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2018/08/there-is-a-safe-level-of-alcohol/568531/">are very small</a> . For heart disease, we see the familiar <i>decrease</i> in risk at moderate drinking levels, and an increase with higher amounts.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2021/07/america-drinking-alone-problem/619017/">From the July/August 2021 issue: America has a drinking problem</a><br><br> <i>None of these results are convincingly causal</i> .<i> </i>It seems very likely that all associations—positive and negative—are overstated relative to the truth. Generally, when researchers are able to adjust for some demographic differences, the relationship between alcohol and health gets smaller. This, in turns, suggests that if they could <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/07350015.2016.1227711">adjust for more differences</a> , it would get smaller still. Whether these relationships would be smaller but still positive, or really zero, is something we cannot know from the data we have.<br><br> We cannot conclusively prove that moderate alcohol consumption is totally benign, much less beneficial. Based on the data we have, it also seems extremely unlikely that moderate alcohol consumption is fully “bad” for your health.<br><br> If you do not enjoy, or actively dislike, alcohol, then the abstinence standard might be the right one for you. But many people do enjoy a drink from time to time: a beer with friends, a cold glass of rosé in the summer, a hot toddy in front of the fire, even just a glass of white wine while cooking at the end of a long day. If we accept that pleasure has value, and that the data are muddy, then the moderation standard makes more sense.<br><br> The pendulum on alcohol has swung too far from the 1990s. Alcohol is probably not the key to longevity. But it&#39;s not arsenic, either. In the immortal words of Cookie Monster, it&#39;s a sometime food.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 14 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/moderate-drinking-heart-disesase-cancer/674692/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/moderate-drinking-heart-disesase-cancer/674692/</item></channel></rss>